<subSubSection pageId="242" pageNumber="243" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="242.[151,1436,1281,2026]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,413,1281,1306]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Description. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[354,413,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Shell</emphasis>
</emphasis>
very small (
<quantity box="[563,656,1281,1306]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" unit="mm" value="7.2">7.2 mm</quantity>
), fusiform (W/L = 
<number box="[883,949,1281,1306]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="0.361">0.361</number>
), glossy smooth, translucent; of about 
<number box="[1401,1414,1281,1305]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="7.0">7</number>
½ strongly convex and moderately elongate whorls, peripheries about mid-whorl, the last about 
<number box="[1230,1258,1318,1342]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="56.0">56</number>
% of total shell length; suture impressed. Sculptural elements only of ribs; aperture narrow, with a short, wide anterior canal and large spout-like anal sinus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[461,595,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Protoconch</emphasis>
of 
<number box="[634,648,1390,1414]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="2.0">2</number>
smooth glossy whorls, the beginning of the first slightly imbedded in the last whorl such that the spire tip appears blunt. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[723,899,1425,1450]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Axial sculpture</emphasis>
of low, opisthocline ribs, about as wide as their interspaces, obsolete on shoulder near suture and fade just below whorl periphery, before suture of succeeding whorl. Rib crests are round. The base of the last whorl is smooth, without ribs. Growth striae microscopic. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1373,1432,1497,1522]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Varix</emphasis>
obscure, the last rib is about ⅓-turn from edge of outer lip. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[869,1059,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Spiral sculpture</emphasis>
absent. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1160,1238,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Sulcus</emphasis>
smooth, without sculpture, flat, not concave. Growth striae, curved reflecting past positions of the anal sinus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1183,1286,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Outer lip</emphasis>
thin, without axial folds, smooth, edge inrolled from anal sinus to beginning of anterior canal; stromboid notch absent. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Anal sinus</emphasis>
a deep notch on whorl shoulder near suture, edge flared and directed laterally, appearing spout-like. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1334,1436,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Inner lip</emphasis>
thin, margined, recumbent; extending over apex of aperture with a weak callus at anal sinus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1203,1372,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Anterior canal</emphasis>
short but well defined, open, unnotched. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[545,610,1713,1738]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Color</emphasis>
translucent white with a light golden brown band mid-whorl, darkened at rib sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="243" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="242.[151,1436,1281,2026]" lastBlockId="243.[151,1436,151,464]" lastPageId="243" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,448,1786,1809]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Remarks. 
<emphasis box="[325,690,1785,1810]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Taxonomy. 
<taxonomicName box="[461,690,1785,1810]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">Lissodrillia fasciata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</emphasis>
has the characteristics of the genus: a small glossy shell with a short anterior canal that lacks spiral sculpture. Unlike most of its congeners, the sulcus is devoid of ribs, which are also quite short for the genus, not extending much past the periphery of the whorl 
<taxonomicName box="[1126,1258,1857,1882]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Splendrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1126,1258,1857,1882]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Splendrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like. Unlike in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,284,1893,1918]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Splendrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,284,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Splendrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
though, this species lacks spiral sculpture and posses a different anal sinus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1134,1298,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Identification.</emphasis>
The species is differentiated from its congeners by its tall narrow spire (overall W/L = 
<number box="[983,1048,1929,1953]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="0.361">0.361</number>
, which is on the narrow end of the range of its congeners), light golden brown mid-whorl band, and flat sulcus that lacks sculpture. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dall, 1881" authorityName="Dall" authorityYear="1881" box="[183,454,2001,2026]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="verrillii">
<emphasis box="[183,301,2001,2026]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">L. verrillii</emphasis>
(Dall, 
<number box="[387,445,2001,2026]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="1881.0">1881</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, which also has convex whorls and a bare sulcus, but that species has more convex whorls, is smaller, and lacks the color band. The strongly convex whorls of 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1180,151,176]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis box="[1057,1180,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="turgida" status="new species">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. turgida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[246,382,188,213]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
but that species is smaller (
<quantity box="[695,796,188,213]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.72" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="4.72">4.72 mm</quantity>
average total length), lacks the flat sulcus, and has more convex ribs. 
<taxonomicName box="[309,542,223,248]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis box="[309,542,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is somewhat similar in form to 
<emphasis box="[951,1059,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">
<taxonomicName box="[951,1055,224,247]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vitrea" status="new species">L. vitrea</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1074,1216,223,248]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
but is larger, has proportionally shorter ribs, and light golden brown mid-whorl band, which is absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1236,261,284]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vitrea">
<emphasis box="[1142,1236,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. vitrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The single wellpreserved 
<typeStatus box="[271,319,296,319]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">type</typeStatus>
specimen has distinctly different morphological characteristics from its congeners as described above. 
<collectingCountry box="[231,262,332,356]" name="American Samoa" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">As</collectingCountry>
the sole representative of the genus in the southeastern Caribbean it was felt that it merited description as new.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="243" pageNumber="244" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="243.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,405,428]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Etymology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[351,587,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis box="[351,587,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Banded 
<taxonomicName box="[766,895,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[766,895,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName box="[1233,1322,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis box="[1233,1322,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning possessing a band, a reference to its mid-whorl color band.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
